dilation","Increased proximal tubular pressure causes afferent arteriole dilation","Decreased proximal tubular flow causes efferent arteriole constriction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tubuloglomerular feedback mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased distal tubular sodium chloride causing afferent arteriole constriction\u003C/strong\u003E. When the macula densa cells detect elevated sodium chloride concentrations, they send paracrine signals to the adjacent afferent arteriole to constrict. This reduces glomerular capillary pressure and filtration rate, helping to prevent excessive fluid and sodium loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased distal tubular potassium causes afferent arteriole dilation\u003C/strong\u003E - Potassium concentration is not the primary signal for tubuloglomerular feedback, as the system specifically responds to sodium chloride levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased distal tubular sodium chloride causes efferent arteriole dilation\u003C/strong\u003E - When sodium chloride levels are low, the feedback mechanism actually causes afferent arteriole dilation to increase filtration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased proximal tubular pressure causes afferent arteriole dilation\u003C/strong\u003E - Tubuloglomerular feedback specifically occurs at the macula densa in the distal tubule, not in the proximal tubule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased proximal tubular flow causes efferent arteriole constriction\u003C/strong\u003E - The efferent arteriole is not directly regulated by the tubuloglomerular feedback mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis negative feedback system helps maintain stable glomerular filtration rate and sodium balance by adjusting filtration in response to tubular sodium chloride levels. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tubuloglomerular feedback system helps to regulate glomerular filtration by sensing sodium chloride concentration in the distal tubule.","Increased sodium chloride at the macula densa triggers afferent arteriole constriction to reduce glomerular filtration rate."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65967"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17683"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65967"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T08:57:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T08:58:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10397"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80671"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}